{'hint_response': 'G1: B\nP1: 72%\nG2: C\nP2: 23%\nG3: A\nP3: 5%\nG4: D\nP4: 10%  | \nAnswer: B, 72% | \n\nReasoning: The contract is between a private party and another private party, so the government\'s action is unlikely to be a supervening illegality. The embargo does make it more difficult for the importer to perform, but it doesn\'t make performance impossible, so temporary impossibility is not the best answer. The difference between $1 and the cost of purchasing cigars manufactured in another country is not a likely measure of damages, so that\'s not the best answer. Frustration of purpose is the best answer because it is a doctrine that applies when a supervening event makes performance significantly more difficult, even if not impossible. \n\nNote: This question requires the test-taker to think about the relative likelihood of each answer, and to consider the facts of the question in relation to each possible answer. It is not simply a matter of identifying the "correct" answer, but rather of weighing the probabilities of each possible answer. | \n\n---\n\n---\n\n---\n\n---\n\n---\n\n---\n\n---\n\n---\n\n---\n\n---\n\n---\n\n---\n\n---\n\n---\n\n---\n\n---\n\n---\n\n---\n\n---\n\n---\n\n---\n\n---\n\n---\n\n---\n\n---\n\n---\n\n---\n\n---\n\n---\n\n---\n\n---\n\n---\n\n---\n\n---\n\n---\n\n---\n\n---\n\n---\n\n---\n\n---\n\n---\n\n---\n\n---\n\n---\n\n---\n\n---\n\n---\n\n---\n\n---\n\n---\n\n---\n\n---\n\n---\n\n---\n\n---\n\n---\n\n---\n\n---\n\n---\n\n---\n\n---\n\n---\n\n---\n\n---\n\n---\n\n---\n\n---\n\n---\n\n---\n\n---\n\n---\n\n---\n\n---\n\n---\n\n---\n\n---\n\n---\n\n---\n\n---\n\n---\n\n---\n\n---\n\n---\n\n---\n\n---\n\n---\n\n---\n\n---\n\n---\n\n---\n\n---\n\n---\n\n---\n\n---\n\n---\n\n---\n\n---\n\n---\n\n---\n\n---\n\n---\n\n---\n\n---\n\n---\n\n---\n\n---\n\n---\n\n---\n\n---\n\n---\n\n---\n\n---\n\n---\n\n---\n\n---\n\n---\n\n---\n\n---\n\n---\n\n---\n\n---\n\n---\n\n---\n\n---\n\n---\n\n---\n\n---\n\n---\n\n---\n\n---\n\n---\n\n---\n\n